name: ** NEW ** Wrap 9 'Telling Tales'
description:
Our NEW winter issue is full of inspiring articles and atmospheric images that explore the theme of folk, traditions and story telling and how these influence creative work today.

PLUS >>

- receive a FREE A5 postcard-print featuring our cover artist Pieter Van Eenoge's excellent illustration (*online exclusive)

- all UK orders will receive FREE post & packing! 


INSIDE ISSUE 9...

- illustrations on our theme by 10 mightily talented creatives: Pieter Van Eenoge (cover artist), Marina Muun, Karol Banach, Sarah Mazzetti, Steffie Brocoli, Viacheslav Vystupov, Pawel Mildner, Leslie Wood, Eleanor Taylor and Assaf Benharroch

- 5 x double sided pull-out wrapping papers (handy for Christmas!)

FEATURES INCLUDE...

- a conversation with Dutch illustrator Merijn Hos about his folk-inspired wooden sculptures

- designer Ya Wen Chou talks about her family heritage, and how it inspires her work today

- we explore the rituals of masquerade that are thriving across Europe and admire incredible photo-portraits by Charles Fréger

- exploring the UK comic scene, we delve into Isabel Greenberg's impressive debut graphic novel 

- Wrap eats a delicious lunch at new London restaurant - Story, and speaks to it's founder Tom Sellers

- five designers tell us the story behind a recent project they've worked on, giving us a great insight into their creative practice
 
.........................................

Designed & published in the UK. Printed on FSC certified paper using vegetable-based inks.

name: Wrap 7 'Drawn Together'
description:
Our spring edition of Wrap looks to creative 'collectives' for its inspiration, and explores the fantastic things that come from people power! 

INSIDE ISSUE SEVEN...

- illustrations on our theme by 10 superbly talented illustration collectives including Nous Vous (cover artists), Edition Biografiktion, Peepshow Collective, Studio Tipi and Hvass&Hannibal

- 5 x double sided exclusive pull-out wrapping papers

FEATURES INCLUDE...

- we meet and photograph some of the team behind Dalston screen-print studio Print Club London

- graphic designer Anthony Burrill introduces Wrap to the old letterpress printers in Rye that he collaborates with to produce his famous posters

- Wrap explores the highs and lows of collaboration through some of London's most inspiring and eclectic team enterprises

- we talk to illustrator and picture book maker Chris Haughton about his fair trade rug project 'Made by Node'

- Wrap pairs up six illustrators to work together to design three notebook covers, and documents the production at Hato Press
 
.........................................

Wrap is designed & published in the UK. We print on FSC certified & recycled paper using vegetable-based inks.

name: Wrap 8 'New Horizons'
description:
Exploring the theme of travel and creative journeys, our summer edition of Wrap – 'New Horizons' – is our biggest yet, at 104 pages! Packed full of inspiring articles and beautiful images created by some of today's most talented illustrators and artists, we hope you'll find it a pleasure to read, as well as to use, because as always Wrap comes with 5 pull-out sheets of wrapping paper.

INSIDE ISSUE 8...

- illustrations on our theme by 10 mightily talented creatives including Martin Nicolausson (cover artist), Natasha Durley, David Doran, Tim Colmant and Olimpia Zagnoli.

- 5 x double sided pull-out wrapping papers

FEATURES INCLUDE...

- we meet the two co-founders of Herb Lester Associates to find out about their growing range of illustrated city guides

- photo-portraits, and mini-interviews with 12 of our favourite new illustration and design graduates

- artist and designer Hannah Waldron tells us about her series of map tapestries that each depict a journey or experience

- Wrap talks to Jeroen Smeets about his crowdfunding-style project The Jaunt, that blends "two of the best things in life – art and travel"

- Burger fanatic Burgerac gives us a passionate account of his travels in search of the tastiest meat treats

- we explore why an increasing number of illustrators are producing pottery alongside their more traditional portfolios of work
 
.........................................

Wrap is designed & published in the UK. 
We print on FSC certified paper using vegetable-based inks.

name: Wrap 5 'Human Endeavours'
description:
Wrap issue five explores the theme of 'Human Endeavours' - aimed at highlighting some of the fantastic physical and creative things that people get up to, from endeavouring to open a new design shop to setting out to reach the South Pole, this issue is jam packed with inspiring content. And, as with every issue of Wrap, we feature the work of ten hugely talented illustrators who have each created an exclusive wrapping paper print to celebrate our 'Human Endeavours' theme, from horse trekking across the Andes to the first slam-dunk in basketball! 

Wrap is published in the UK - we print on FSC certified & recycled paper using vegetable-based inks. We've printed a limited run of 3,000 copies of issue five, and every issue is hand-numbered.

name: 'Building Blocks' giclée print
description:
Originally created for Wrap issue 7, 'Building Blocks' has been drawn by the brilliant Danish collective Hvass&Hannibal:

"The concept behind our print is to show how creative work is all about assembling the ‘building blocks’ you have to hand, represented here by wooden objects. It is depicted like a game, to convey that playfulness is an important part of creative work – and that building, taking down, and rearranging is all part of the creative process." Nan Na Hvass, Co-founder of Hvass&Hannibal 

– 70cm X 50cm
- Giclée printed for best quality on 300gsm paper
- Limited edition of 25

description:

"We are working on an exhibition that will open in May 2013, which is also called Spectral Nation, and will explore some of our usual themes such as wormholes into other dimensions. This print is a visual representation of what the insides of our brains are looking like right now! And, being screen printers, we generally have to limit ourselves to three to five colours, so we thought we'd grab this opportunity to use as many as possible." – Luke Frost, founding member of Heretic
